<br>
Not really.  Their $15 a month is just as good as your $15 a month.<br>
<br>
There is a good argument that those who play more often or longer should get more rewards.  But there is also an argument that the people who spend 6-8 hours a day playing the game create a significantly higher drain on resources than those who play only 2 hours a day.  This could be viewed as making their $15 worth more by costing less resources.<br>
<br>
In any case, I don't see how EQ2 is restricting powergamers in the slightest.  There will still be solo content, and all classes will be able to solo--not just the wizards, necros and enchanters.<br>
<br>
You will not get <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>better</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> experience by soloing instead of grouping.  In fact, grouping will likely be the preferred method of gaining experience just because of this fact.  I imagine that a mob will be worth a certain amount of xp, and each person, regardless of how many are in the group, will receive that amount.  But this has not been confirmed.<br>
<br>
Locked encounters are what I think EQ should be.  It's your group against a group of mobs.  Your resources vs. theirs.  The concentration factor of spells will help with this as well.  I see nothing wrong with this system.  In fact, I see everything <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>right</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with this system. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://webpages.charter.net/thewok/jarasig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
