<br>
This is the same combat system used by most video game RPGs.  You enter an encounter with the monsters, nothing else joins unless it's a special event, and your party proceeds to hack at them and vice versa.<br>
<br>
In the face of this system though, strategy tends to go bye bye.  Over the 20-60 hours that it takes to finish most of these RPGs, that doesn't necessarily bother me.  When talking about a game that I could conceivably be playing for years though, it might very well bore me to death.  Will have to see <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jaranna>Jaranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/23/03 8:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2250.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: .</span><hr size=1> On the contrary, I see more need for strategy with a limited group than with just asking for help from some passerby.<br>
